d><gtr:title>The Development of Proposals for a Robust Rural Evidence Base to Underpin Rural Policy Making in Northern Ireland</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0096</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>In September 2008 Sally Shortall was appointed ESRC fellow on placement in the Department of Agriculture and Rural Development, Northern Ireland. The title of the project is: The Development of Proposals for a Robust Rural Evidence Base to Underpin Rural Policy Making in Northern Ireland. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The main objectives of the project are described by the DARDNI as: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>To examine the existing rural evidence base of economic and social studies used to underpin rural policymaking in Northern Ireland and identify evidence/ research gaps.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To identify the priority themes and indicators for future research to address these gaps in the evidence base. &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To develop models for the most efficient and effective methods of collecting, using and disseminating rural evidence and research. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>Dr. Shortall will examine policy questions such as rural proofing, the development of a Rural White Paper, and what we mean by sustainable rural communities. She will also consider the linkages between academic knowledge and policy formation.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>An Advisory Group has been established and will meet four times during the life of the research. Three academic think-tank meetings will also be convened. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

